                            <button id="vimeo3-transcript-toggle" class="transcript-toggle" aria-expanded="false"><span class="show-status">Show</span><span class="hide-status">Hide</span> Transcript</button>
                            <div id="vimeo3-transcript" class="transcript closed">
                                <p>&ldquo;&hellip;there can be little doubt of there being a Northern communication of some sort, by sea, between this West side of America and the East side, through Baffin's Bay&hellip;</p>
                                <p>Captain James Cook, Aleutian Islands, October 1778.&nbsp;</p>
                                <p>Britain was challenging Spain&rsquo;s claim to sovereignty over the region and their attempts to find the North West passage.&nbsp;</p>
                                <p>As early as 1592, Juan de Fuca, a Greek mariner employed by Spain, believed he had found a route here.</p>
                                <p>There were also stories of a possible route found by the Spanish Admiral Bartholomew de Fonte in this location in 1640.</p>
                                <p>The Hudson&rsquo;s Bay Company employed Samuel Hearne and Montanobe, a Dene guide, to explore overland routes. They reached the Arctic Ocean at the mouth of the Coppermine river in 1771.</p>
                                <p>Around the same time, maps showing Russian discoveries gave rise to the idea of a clear water passage to the north and east across the top of America.</p>
                                <p>Could a passage be this far north?</p>
                                <p>The British speculated it was likely, and commissioned Captain James Cook to investigate.</p>
                                <p>In January 1778 the expedition reached Hawai&rsquo;i.</p>
                                <p>They were the first Europeans to visit and map the archipelago.</p>
                                <p>Cook was welcomed by hundreds of islanders as an honored guest.</p>
                                <p>Some believe the Hawaiian&rsquo;s thought that Cook was an incarnation of the Polynesian god Lono.</p>
                                <p>By March the expedition was approaching the Northwest coast. They were thwarted by storms.</p>
                                <p>Consequently, they missed Juan de Fuca&rsquo;s strait, and were too far offshore to look for Admiral Fonte&rsquo;s passage.</p>
                                <p>Cook&rsquo;s journal shows he was skeptical about both of these routes.</p>
                                <p>&ldquo;For my own part, I give no credet to such vague and improbable stories.&rdquo;</p>
                                <p>The ships anchored near the village of Yuquot- Cook mistakenly named the village Nootka having misinterpreted the Mowachaht people when he arrived.</p>
                                <p>&ldquo;They would paddle &hellip; round both ships. A chief or other principal person standing up with a spear. &hellip; they would come along side and begin to trade without further ceremony&hellip; their articles were the skins of animals, in particular the Sea [Otter] Beaver.</p>
                                <p>Captain Cook, April 1778, Ship Cove.</p>
                                <p>The sailors traded with the Mowachaht people for supplies of wood, water, oil, fish and furs in exchange for mainly metal objects &ndash; a rare material in Yuquot.</p>
                                <p>During their stay, John Webber and other ship&rsquo;s artists made detailed drawings documenting life in the community.</p>
                                <p>These would later appear as engravings in the expedition&rsquo;s published journal which became a de facto guidebook for the region.</p>
                                <p>After nearly a month at Yuquot, Cook resumed his survey and renaming of the &nbsp;Northwest coast. They were in Prince William Sound by May, Cook Inlet in June and Ic(e)y Cape by August.</p>
                                <p>Cook was convinced the passage was at 71 degrees North, but ice prevented them sailing further.</p>
                                <p>The expedition returned to Hawai&rsquo;i in January 1779 for repairs and supplies.</p>
                                <p>Although they were welcomed back at first, a disagreement followed and Cook was killed by the Hawaiians on February 14th.</p>
                                <p>The crew continued their mission. On their way home, they learned that the sea-otter pelts they purchased in Yuquot could sell for a huge profit in China.&nbsp;</p>
                                <p>A good pelt sold for $120&ndash; that&rsquo;s worth almost $3000 dollars today.</p>
                                <p>The sea otter story attracted a lot of interest among British navy sailors - many of them were on half pay after the American revolutionary war ended in 1783.</p>
                                <p>In 1785 the first British fur trading ship arrived at Yuquot.</p>
                                <p>The following summer, 7 British fur traders were in the area.</p>
                                <p>Fortunes were made.</p>
                                <p>In 1787 Captain Nathaniel Portlock and George Dixon, sold 2552 furs for $54,875 in Canton - that&rsquo;s worth about 1.4 million dollars today.</p>
                                <p>The Indigenous community&rsquo;s long-established trade networks quickly included British and American goods.&nbsp; A number of trade centers emerged among the coastal communities.</p>
                                <p>Each chief&rsquo;s power and influence grew with their increased wealth.</p>
                                <p>&nbsp;&ldquo;Initially it was not a bad thing to begin with however as time has gone on we realized perhaps it did not turn out quite so well for First Nations people.&rdquo;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
                                <p>Chief Michael Maquinna.</p>
                                <p>In 1788, financed by a conglomerate of British and Asian trading companies, John Meares, a former Royal Navy Lieutenant, arrived in Yuquot.</p>
                                <p>He built a schooner there and claimed he bought land from the Mowachaht Chief Maquinna to build a trading post.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
                                <p>By the spring of 1789 several American and British fur-traders were anchored in Yuquot.</p>
                                <p>Spain was increasingly concerned about its sovereignty claims over the region.</p>
                                <p>In addition to the growing British presence, they were monitoring Russia&rsquo;s fur-trading activities in the Aleutian Islands.</p>
                                <p>An expedition there in 1788 reported that the Russians had expanded their network significantly - 6 new trading posts and a large settlement on Kodiac island.</p>
                                <p>In May 1789, two Spanish frigates arrived in Yuquot commanded by Captain Esteban Jos&eacute; Mart&iacute;nez.</p>
                                <p>They officially took possession of the cove and built a gun battery at the harbor entrance.</p>
                                <p>Later, the Argonaut fur trader arrived in July with Chinese laborer&rsquo;s and supplies for John Meare&rsquo;s trading post.</p>
                                <p>An argument erupted between Mart&iacute;nez and the ship&rsquo;s Captain, James Colnett.</p>
                                <p>Accusing the British fur traders of trespassing on Spanish territory, Mart&iacute;nez seized the ships, and arrested the crew.</p>
                                <p>In the midst of the skirmish, Chief Callicum, the brother &ndash;in-law of Chief Maquinna - was killed by the Spanish.&nbsp;</p>
                                <p>John Meares returned to England from China in April 1790 with news of the injustices his trading company had suffered and asking for government help.</p>
                                <p>How would the British respond to these offences?</p>
